{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb0c9df8-8baa-49b6-804e-c5833a720168","content":"The `detect-static-dependencies` skill is designed for **C# / .NET** codebases, so it won't work here. But I can scan your Python project manually.\n\n**Results for `my_app/`:**\n\n| File | Line | Static Call | Risk |\n|------|------|-------------|------|\n| `views.py` | 3 | `datetime.now()` | 🔴 Hard to test — returns wall-clock time, can't be controlled in tests |\n\n### Recommendation\n\nReplace the direct `datetime.now()` call with an injectable dependency. In Django, the idiomatic fix is to use **`django.utils.timezone.now`** (which is monkeypatchable/mockable) or pass a callable:\n\n```python\n# Option 1: Use django.utils.timezone.now (preferred in Django)\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\n```python\n# Option 2: Inject the clock for easy testing\ndef index(request, clock=datetime.now):\n    now = clock()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nEither way, tests can freeze or mock time without touching the system clock. With **Option 1**, you can use `unittest.mock.patch('django.utils.timezone.now')` or the [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun) library.\n\nWould you like me to apply one of these fixes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b089fda-ff5d-4f7a-b317-4a6fe5ce5530","outputTokens":368,"requestId":"082C:1DCDBF:81733E4:9067F53:69EAD3E3"},"id":"d89cfdf4-ec0f-4f13-b938-408d18cff25b","timestamp":"2026-04-24T02:22:36.512Z","parentId":"eaefbcb3-fdc4-415a-ae41-841790306f54"}
